<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 19:07:50 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I recently retired from the Air Force.  I never went to Vietnam.  I came in after it ended.  I've been to the wall several times while stationed in D.C. or while visiting.  I don't know anyone who died there.  I have a few friends that served there.  I have taken all three of my daughters, one at a time, to the wall to try to explain what it is and why it is.  It makes the hair on my neck stand up each time I go.  We have to learn from this or we will end up doing it again.  As wars go in the number of those killed it doesn't compare to WWI, WWII, or the Civil War, but in the damage it did to our faith in our government and our selves, it almost qualifies as a civil war.  Th e wall conveys an appropriate message, one that is different for everyone that visits it.
<p><code>-- DJM 27@aol.com  (David Manship) </code><p>


